<!--ARTICLE SECTION CONTAINS h,p,img-->  
        <div class="article">
             <div class="paragraph">
                <p> We take an Uber and drive to the hotel.It feels like we are driving through an endless construction site. Here the Country is being built - everywhere, on every street, corner and any place. Already forty 
                    years building it. Much of the desert is now covered by futuristic buildings and hundreds of skyscrapers surrounded by clouds.
                    This small territory (Qatar is only 11,571 km2) has the third largest natural gas reserves in the world, as well as a significant amount of oil. This together with
                    its modest population (2.782 million) has made Qatar the richest country in the world in terms of GDP per capita. Interesting that number of non-citizens exceeds 
                    85%. Upon arrival at hotel the receptionist upgrades our room to a higher class as she is pleasantly surprised that we are not just usual transfer guests but exactly Qatar 
                    is our main destination. We fall asleep watching the newly created Qatar and its splendor. A few decades ago, before the flaming oil owers, there were definitely 
                    some desert travelers sitting around the bonfire.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="imageBlog">
                <a href="/Qatar_part_I/Picture 008.jpg"><img src="/Qatar_part_I/Picture 008.jpg"></a>
            </div>
        </div>
<!-- CONTENT ENDS-->

<!--ARTICLE SECTION CONTAINS h,p,img-->  
         <div class="article">
            <div class="heading">
                <h2>Good morning Doha!</h2>
            </div>
            <div class="paragraph">
                <p> Daily plan is adventurous off-road car tour in the desert. However, though it is February and the air temperature does not reach 40+ degrees as in summer, even in winter the middle 
                    of the day can be very sultry, so first we go to the National Museum of Qatar.
                    Once arriving there I quickly realized that by giving museum only supporting role in our adventure is a mistake. We need more than an hour just to see the building itself and its surroundings.
                    Inspired by the "dessert rose" - the sand crystal formation found in Qatar, the French architect Jean Nouvel has created an amazing desert flower.</p>
                <p> When we get inside the museum we have just 40 minutes left which would deserve to be at least three times longer duration. Expositions are modern, interactive and very engaging.
                    Unfortunately we have to go.</p>
            </div>   
            <div class="imageBlog">
                <a href="/Qatar_part_I/Picture 009.jpg"><img src="/Qatar_part_I/Picture 009.jpg"></a>
